  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "iNaturalist data are best suited for occurrence, phenology, and broad distribution questions. They are weak for abundance, population trends, and causality without additional structure.\n¶What iNaturalist data can support Range extensions or confirmations. Phenological timing of flowering, migration, or emergence. Presence-only modeling with appropriate bias correction. Early warning signals when paired with targeted follow-up surveys. ¶What iNaturalist data cannot support alone Abundance or density estimates. Absence-based inference without structured effort. Fine-scale demographic conclusions. ¶Fit-for-purpose checklist Is your question compatible with presence-only data? Do you have a plan to model or correct sampling bias? Are you combining iNaturalist with structured datasets where needed? ¶Strengths and pitfalls in analysis Strengths:\n",
  "name": "Limits: what iNaturalist data can and cannot support",
